<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-help-w2-printing-error-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">&ldquo;W-2 printing error,&rdquo; plainly.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>A W-2 is the year-end wage and tax statement QuickBooks generates from your payroll data for each employee. When people say W-2 printing &ldquo;isn&rsquo;t working,&rdquo; they usually mean one of a few things: the W-2s <em>won&rsquo;t print</em> at all; the text <em>misaligns</em> on a pre-printed form so the boxes don&rsquo;t line up; or the form <em>won&rsquo;t generate</em> because the current-year W-2 version isn&rsquo;t available or the payroll service isn&rsquo;t active.</p>
      <p>The good news is that most of these trace to a short list of causes, and the self-fix steps below address them in order of likelihood &mdash; updating QuickBooks and payroll so the current-year form is available clears a large share of cases. What the steps <em>can&rsquo;t</em> fix is the underlying problem when the W-2 numbers themselves are wrong: payroll figures that don&rsquo;t tie to the books, missing employee data, or a year-end that&rsquo;s a mess. That part is a ProAdvisor job, not a reprint. And the actual filing of W-2s with the SSA &mdash; plus copies to employees &mdash; follows the IRS/SSA process through Intuit&rsquo;s payroll e-file or your CPA; an Intuit account, subscription, or e-services matter stays with Intuit.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

